{{Other uses|Needle drop (disambiguation){{!}}Needle drop}}
A '''needle drop''' is a version of a music [[album]] that has been transferred from a [[vinyl record]] to [[digital audio]] or other formats. Needle drops are sometimes traded among music collectors, especially when the original vinyl recording has not been released officially on a subsequent consumer format. It is also referred to as a ''''Vinyl Rip'''' or ''''Record Rip''''
Other reasons for trading needle drops include the lack of availability of certain [[Sound recording|recordings]] on [[digital media]], the non-availability of less [[Dynamic range compression|compressed]] versions in digital form, or the lack of availability of certain versions or [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mixes]] of that [[Sound recording|record]], e.g. [[Monaural|mono]] or [[stereo]] versions, or the loss of the [[master tape]].<ref name="Label vault problems">{{Cite web |url=http://www.billholland.net/words/Labels%20Strive%20to%20Rectify%20Past%20Archival%20Problems.pdf |title=Labels strive to rectify past problems |accessdate=November 5, 2008 |work=[[Billboard Magazine]] |year=2007 |author=Bill Holland |format=[[Portable Document Format|PDF]]}}</ref> The term is thought to have been coined in 1949 by [[Peter Carl Goldmark|Peter Goldmark]] during the first rush of transfers of lacquer and [[Gramophone record#78 rpm disc developments|78 RPM records]] to the then-new long playing [[Gramophone record#New sizes and materials|33 ⅓ RPM format]].
